MissionCommands.Message: [This mission comes with custom checklists that has been added to your Mission Pad for the duration of this mission only]

[Freddo has been up receiving the Entry, LM Prep, EI Minus 6 hours procedures for the Lunar Module activation and entry preparation. You can find the procedures in the LM CHECKLIST/AOH, under MISSION.]
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead, Houston.

Okay, Skipper. We figured out a way for you to keep warm. We decided to start powering you up now, and what we want you to do - what we want you to do is take your entry LM Prep checklist and start at the top where it says "Bat 5 Normal FEED on," and then jump over as it says to your 30-minute activation, and do all of the 30-minute activation up to, but not including, the burn. You copy?

Okay. If I understand you correctly, then that gives me leeway to maneuver when we get up to activation complete, and we can be in position for the burn, but we will not burn. We don't have a PAD anyway.
That's affirm, Jim. You could maneuver to burn attitude, or you could maneuver to an attitude which should put the Sun in the windows to warm the place up.

[You will now run the modified 30-minutes activation checklist with a few modifications Fred made while the rest was "sleeping". You can find the checklist in the LM CHECKLIST(AOH) > MISSION > A13 LM ACTIVATION section]
[RUN the A13 LM ACTIVATION checklist now, until the SET MISSION TIMERs step.]
Okay, Houston. We'd like to get a hack to set our mission timer here, Jack.
Okay, Freddo. Set it at 133:35 straight up.

[STOP the Mission Timer, set it to 133:35:00. When MCC tells you to start it, start it. Press OK and use time scale to get closer. If you have passed it, sync them using the function bubble button "SYNC MET TIMERS"]
Okay. Standing by.
Okay. I'll give you the 2-second delay in there. Stand by to start.
Start.
[Press the SYNC MET TIMERS function bubble in the LM COCKPIT just to be sure the MET are correctly synced.]
And, Houston, Aquarius. I guess the next thing for the PGNS will be a coarse align 000, but I guess we ought to hold up now until we get enough time on the RCS thrusters.
Roger. We're looking at them. We'll give you the Go on them.
Okay, Aquarius. Your quads are 120 to 133 now, so you're cleared for - Cleared for thrusters.
That's affirm. We're Go. What we're doing now, Jack, is letting the spacecraft drift in this mode to pick up the Earth again.
[Continue with the checklist until you are instructed to damp the rates. At this point, wait for the Earth to show up in the window, then center it in the COAS and damp the rates.]
[Align the Earth to burn attitud, with the Earth crescent aligned with the horizontal COAS line]
Aquarius, your ASA is warmed up now. You can activate the AGS.
[Complete the checklist]
And, it's getting a little warmer in here now. Thank you.
Duck blinds are always warmer, Jim, when the birds are flying.
Aquarius, something we're thinking about right now is, if we can do it without using a lot of RCS, it would be to our advantage timewise to try to get an alignment.
I'll see what we can do, Jack.
Okay. And we'd planned to use the Moon and the Sun for that.
Jack, it sounds good. I think from our position here, we know where the Sun and Moon are and it's strictly going to be a pitch maneuver. But I think we can save some gas. I'll see what we can do.
Are you going to ship us up a REFSMMAT?
Yes, we are. Stand by 1.
The Sun feels wonderful. It's shining in the rendezvous window.
And, Aquarius, before we can ship you a load, we'll have to have, on panel 11, under Comm, the Updata Link circuit breaker closed.
It's closed.
Roger. Aquarius, we're through with it, it's your computer.
Thank you.
And, Aquarius, Houston; take option 1 on a P52 when you get to it. [Key V37E 52E]
[Key V22E +1E PRO PRO, return to P00]
[Fred will complete the procedure, you will need to maneuver as requested]
Pitch up towards the sun, and center the sun in the COAS. [Press MARK when the sun is centered in your COAS]
Okay, Houston. We have the Sun marks and I'll start up at pitch now to go over and pick up the Moon.
Roger.
Continue to pitch up and center the Moon in the COAS. [Press MARK when the Moon is centered in the COAS]
Looks to us like you've got her aligned, Jim
Yeah. I'm pretty confident that the platform's fairly decent.

Aquarius, Houston. We think we've figured out a way to save you some time at a very critical - very full schedule. And that's by doing a docked coarse align, since we got the LM up now. That would save you a maneuver or two.
Houston, Aquarius. It seemed to me a docked coarse align might be quicker for - for Jack.
Yeah. We think it would be, and it'd save quite a bit of time at a place where you're going to be pretty busy. Also save you some petrol.
Affirm.
Okay, Jim. We're looking at doing this in the Service Module Sep attitude, and the optics will be pointed away from the Sun. So it should be a good attitude for a P52.
Okay. So, we'll be going to the Service Module Sep attitude, at which time we'll do a docked coarse align, and then you want - You want Jack then to do a P52?

The way we'll do that in our time line Jim, is to go ahead and do the Service Module Jett and then we'll just stay in that attitude and when it comes time in our time line as we've outlined, to bring the platform up, we'll proceed with the P52 - coarse align, and then the P52.
And, Aquarius. One thing, however, that we do not plan to do is to proceed with the Command Module power-up prematurely.
Roger.
Understand.
Okay, Houston. This is Jack.
Go ahead, Jack.
Okay. I just wanted to talk over with you, it looks like we've had some changes in the Flight Plan here, due to Jim's P52. Do you have - Can you talk over with me what your plans are?

Roger, Jack. Since we've got the PGNS up, we plan to use that information to give the CMC a dock coarse align, and then we're in the Service Module jettison attitude, we'll wait until it comes time to power up the CMC ...

And we'll get the CMC a dock coarse align, and we'll pick some good stars to give you a fine align with, and it looks like we can pick some stars that are looking away from the Sun in which you can find in that Service Module jettison attitude; so, we'll save you quite a bit of gas, and save you some time in a very busy time.
Hey, that sounds good. Really fine.
Aquarius, Houston. Over.
Go ahead, Houston.
Okay, Jim. I got MCC-7 PAD when you're ready to copy. Over.
Okay. Stand by.
[Press READY to proceed]
Okay. We're in luck, I got one PAD left.
Okay. We'll take care not to change this one. Ready to go?
Go ahead, Joe.

MCC-7: 137:39:48.39, minus 0003.1, plus all zeros, plus 00001, N/A, plus 0020.5, 0003.1, 0:23, 008, 359; the rest is N/A. Remarks: plus-X, four jets, RCS; and your weights for the DAP load: LM weight, 25181; CSM weight, 62468. Over.

Okay, Joe. MCC-7: 137:39:48.39, minus 0003.1, plus all balls, plus 0000.1, N/A, plus 0020.5, plus 0003.1, 0:23, 008, 359; the rest of pad N/A. Remarks: plus-X, four jets, RCS, ullage; the LM weight, 25181; CSM weight, 62468. Over.
And, Aquarius; Houston. I have a Service Module Sep PAD if you want to copy that, now. Over.
[This will just be an attitude and can be written down in the Mission Pad -> NOTES section or on a piece of paper]
Okay. The PAD reads as follows and then I'll repeat the angles for you so you can copy them. The following MCC-7, maneuver the LM to the following FDAI attitudes: roll, 000; pitch, 91.3; yaw, 000.
Okay. Following MCC-7 we're to maneuver to the following attitudes: roll, 000; pitch, 091.3; yaw, 000.

Okay. That's correct. And the last part of the PAD is at GET 138:10:00, which is EI minus 4.5 hours, execute a push of 0.5 feet per second, four jet, plus-X; perform SM Sep; then execute pull, 0.5 feet per second, four jet, minus-X. Over.

Okay. That last Joe was execute at the GET at 138:10:00 which is EI minus 4½ hours; execute a push of 0.5 feet per second, four-jet ullage; then execute SM Sep followed by a pull of 0.5 feet per second, with respect to a nomenclature on the TTCA; I think we really need an up of 0.5 and then a down of 0.5.
Houston, Aquarius. Jack's entering the Command Module, now.
Okay, Jim. [This is the EI-6+30 mark, and the start of the Command Module power up]
Okay, Aquarius. The last PAD I had for you right now is the LM jettison PAD.
Okay. Go ahead, Joe. [Press READY to proceed]

Okay, Fred. Prior to 141:40:00, which is EI minus 1 hour, maneuver the LM to the following FDAI angles: roll, 130; pitch, 125; yaw, 012.4. The corresponding CSM gimbal angles will be roll, 291; pitch, 196; yaw, 045, and that's the PAD. Over.
Okay. A LM Sep PAD prior to 141:40:00, EI minus 1 hour, maneuver to following attitudes: roll, 130; pitch, 125; yaw, 012.4. The corresponding CSM gimbal angles are roll, 291; pitch, 196; yaw, 045.
[Go into the CM. The Odeyssy Power Up sequence is about to start. You will follow a MISSION checklist added into the COMMAND MODULE/AOH checklist tab -> A13: CM EI-6+30. Find the checklist now]
[RUN the checklist now]
[Complete the checklist]
Aquarius, Houston.
Go ahead, Houston.
Roger. We're looking at LM current, to see if Jack has started his preheat, and we haven't seen it yet. Is he doing okay down there?
This has been started and in about 1 minute it should have been on for 20 minutes.
Houston, Jack said he's already started it, and he said that in 1 more minute, he'll be up to 20 minutes.
Oh. Roger that.
Do you see a current now, Houston?
Stand by 1 on that, Jim. That's affirmative, Jim; it looks like we are seeing one now.
Okay. And thanks for keeping us on it.
[Switch back into the CM. The next procedure will terminate the CM RCS PREHEAT]
[Switch back into the LM]
We recommend at this time that you do an AGS to PGNS align, the 400 plus 3 procedure only. Over.
Okay.
[The next procedure will use the AGS to align the AGS platform with the IMU platform]
DEDA: Key 400+3E
Roger. We recommend that you perform this burn in AGS, as you did the last midcourse maneuver; we think it will save gas. Over.
Okay. Joe, do you want me to line up the same way we did the last one, too?
[While powering up the CM, there was a conversation about the possibility of doing the burn in PGNS, but it was decided to to this in AGS.]

Okay. Here's the big story. We'd like you to trim to zero pitch; to 008 degrees in roll; and to zero degrees in yaw. Then we'd like you to do the body-axis align 400 plus 5, 400 plus 0. Pitch and Roll to Pulse, select AGS, do the burn in AGS. How does that sound? Over.
[Maneuver to burn attitude: 8° roll, 0° yaw, 0° pitch and damp rates]
[AGS/DEDA: 400+5E]
[AGS/DEDA: 400+0E]
Aquarius, Houston. Your attitude looks real good. We will give you a mark at 10 minutes to the burn, which is in 28 seconds.
Okay. We'll burn it in AGS and use the AGS ball. [Stop the the Digital Event Timer, set the Timer to 9 minutes, and to countdown]
Right. I was looking at the wrong clock, and we're a little under 10 minutes now. I'll give you a mark at 9 minutes. Okay?
That's fine. [Be prepared to start the timer]
Aquarius, Houston. We have 10 seconds until 9 minutes to the burn. 3, 2, 1... Mark. [Start the Event Timer] Nine minutes.
Okay, Houston. About 3 minutes to go, and we're all squared away.
[Set the Throttle Control to AUTO]

[Prepare for the burn, it will be a burn where you use the translation jets to burn in the UP direction [I]. While the AGS is in works, open the Mission Pad -> Map, and take a look at your Pe. Burn UP until this equals 20.5 nautical miles]
And, Aquarius; Houston. Roger that. And we're standing by for your body-axis align and your zeroing 404, 405, 406, going to 470.
[Prepare for the burn, zero the attitude on the AGS FDAI]
[Ignition! Start the burn]
We're burning.
Copy that, Fred.
[Complete the burn, and tweak the data so Pe is 20.5 nautical miles using the Mission Pad -> Map view. This implementation will be iterated on later. Press DONE when the burn is complete]
Okay. That's it.
Okay. If you're happy, can we maneuver to Service Module Sep attitude now?
That's affirmative, Aquarius.
[Pitch up to the SM SEP attitude from the PAD: roll, 000; pitch, 91.3; yaw, 000.]
And I'm pitching up to the proper attitude.
Okay. We're looking at it.
[When at the attitude, damp rates and maintain attitude]
[Press ROGER when the maneuver is complete.]
[This completes the mission, the journey continues in the next and last mission of the campaign]

Title: MISSION 22 - MCC 7
Description: The final midcourse correction will place the spacecraft on a trajectory with an angle of 6.5 degrees at entry interface. The crew must complete the burn for a safe entry.
BriefingText:
Primary objectives:
• to perform selenological inspection, survey, and sampling of
materials in a preselected region of the Fra Mauro formation;
• to deploy and activate an Apollo lunar surface experiments package;
• to further develop human capability to work in the lunar environment; and
• to obtain photographs of candidate exploration sites.

You can find the documnets needed here:https://www.nasa.gov/history/afj/ap13fj/a13-documents.html
